status_message:
How do you save water?

With mandatory water restrictions on the horizon, many Californians will need to figure out how to reduce their home water use or face big penalties. We want to hear from you: If you've already cut your water use dramatically, how did you do it? If you need to do a better job conserving water, do you have a strategy in mind? Or are you at a loss where to start? Email reporter Nicholas Weiler at nweiler@mercurynews.com with your comments. Please include your phone number and the best time to reach you if you are willing to be interviewed for an upcoming article.

status_message:
Anxious about its ability to plan where to locate schools, the San Jose Unified School District plans to sue the Santa Clara County Board of Education for allowing Rocketship Education to build a K-5 charter school next to the Tamien light rail station in San Jose.

San Jose Unified officials emphasized that the suit is not intended to halt charter schools in general or Rocketship, which runs seven charter elementary schools in San Jose, in particular.

"It's really not about charters," said San Jose Unified Superintendent Vincent Matthews, a former charter school administrator. "It's about the county making a decision that we don't believe they have the authority to make."

Read more of reporter Sharon Noguchi's story: http://bit.ly/Vwq3O7
Photograph by Nhat V. Meyer

If you have recently lived in poverty and are willing to share your story about it, please contact reporter Matt O'Brien at mattobrien@bayareanewsgroup.com or 510-293-2465.

Any 3-person family making less than about $18,000 a year is considered to be living below the (2011) federal poverty line; for a 2-person family the threshold is $14,667; for 1 person, $11,491; and for a 4-person family, $23,018.

The U.S. Census Bureau will release its annual poverty statistics on Wednesday.

status_message: What's your technology threshold? As tech devices continue to bless/encroach on our lives, we find we all have individual thresholds/quirks/biases about what is reasonable tech use in quasi-public places. Take the recent incident at Facebook offices, where a yoga instructor was fired for allegedly glaring at a student who was texting during class -- some people don't see a problem with that kind of thing, while it drives others nuts. Society seems to be working out its own rules on thing like cell phones in movies and restaurants, but it's not so obvious elsewhere. If you have a strong opinion on this, BANG staff writer Angela Hill would love to contact you for a brief interview by the end of the day today. Reach her at ahill@bayareanewsgroup.com or 510-208-6493.

Restored mining landmark reopens at Santa Clara County park
http://www.mercurynews.com/top-stories/ci_16596145

If walls could talk, the historic Casa Grande would have tales to tell -- of money and mercury, laughter and loss. And then it was all gone, turning California's first, richest and longest-running mine into a mere footnote of history.

These and other stories will be recounted, after two years of silence, in an event Saturday to celebrate the re-opening of the newly renovated mansion and museum of the New Almaden Quicksilver Mines.

Brian Wilson has defined the look, attitude and style of play for a Giants team on a roll
http://www.mercurynews.com/giants/ci_16343517

When Giants closer Brian Wilson walks around his San Francisco neighborhood, people approach him with a look of recognition.

"They'll come up to me and say, 'Hey, you're that guy, the guy with the beard. I don't know baseball, but good luck, man. This is awesome,' " Wilson said.

The quirky reliever is impossible to miss with his tattoos, faux-Mohawk hairstyle and surreal beard that appears to be colored with black shoe polish.

Do you believe in extraterrestrials?

Sean Webby writes: Is sending signals to aliens really a good idea? If we are
 not alone in the universe, then -- considering what happened to the 
Indians after Columbus landed in America -- shouldn't we be keeping a 
pretty low profile?

That's one of the burning questions in the 
current scientific search for intelligent extraterrestrial life. The 
question was debated in front of an enthusiastic crowd of scientists, 
teachers and amateurs at a SETI Institute conference in Santa Clara over
 the weekend.

Happy Wanderer: A ride back into time at Wild Horse Sanctuary
http://www.mercurynews.com/bay-area-living/ci_15682803

Ginny Prior writes: When you think of Northern California, cowboys and cattle drives are probably not the first things that pop into your mind. But there's a place outside Redding that perfectly captures the romance of the Old West. It's the Wild Horse Sanctuary near Shingletown, about a half-hour's drive from Lassen Volcanic National Park. Here, on 5,000 acres of mountain meadow and forest, 300 wild mustangs roam freely across a rugged land with soaring vistas and sky as big as a Montana sunset. 

(Photo archive credit: Ginny Prior/For Bay Area News Group)

status_message:
Saratoga: Comerica Bank robber sought
http://www.mercurynews.com/top-stories/ci_15363545

Santa Clara County Sheriff's deputies are asking anyone who recognizes a distinctive logo on a bank robber's T-shirt to call in and identify a muscular, bald man who walked into a Comerica Bank on Tuesday in Saratoga and biked off with a bundle of cash.

Sgt. Rick Sung also said the robber might have red dye all over his fingers and clothes, as the bank teller secretly slipped a red dye pack into the stack of stolen cash.

The suspect, who may have been armed, entered the bank on Saratoga-Sunnyvale Road about 3:30 p.m. and handed the teller a note indicating he was robbing the bank, authorities said.

Video surveillance inside the bank shows clear pictures of a white man in good athletic shape with a shaved head, sunglasses, white shorts and athletic shoes. He looks to be 6 feet 2 inches tall and 230 pounds and perhaps in his late 30s. The background of the shirt he's wearing is dark blue or black, and the logo looks possibly like a shield with either swords or lacrosse sticks crossing over each other to make an X.

The suspect was last seen on a mountain bike. Authorities also believe, without disclosing further detail, that he may have committed a similar robbery at a Bank of the West branch in San Jose on Saturday.

Anyone with information on this incident can call Sgt. Herman Leon at 408-808-4500 during normal business hours or 408-808-4410 after hours. Those wishing to remain anonymous can call the sheriff's tip line at 408-808-4431.

Photo caption: Photograph of suspect in robbery at Comerica Bank in Saratoga.  ( Santa Clara County Sheriff's Dep )

http://www.mercurynews.com/top-stories/ci_15361926

Gary Richards reports: Get ready for a new way of commuting, one that will allow drivers traveling alone to buy their way out of traffic jams for the first time in the Bay Area.

Beginning Sept. 20, solo drivers can skirt backups on southbound Interstate 680 on the Sunol Grade by paying a toll to use the faster-moving carpool lane.

Alameda County officials unveiled the details Wednesday: Tolls will be in effect from 5 a.m. to 8 p.m. Monday through Friday and could range from 30 to 50 cents to $5 or $6 for the 14-mile trek from Highway 84 in Pleasanton to Highway 237 in Milpitas.

status_message:
San Jose airport makeover includes lots of high-tech amenities

John Boudreau reports: A nearly completed billion-dollar-plus face lift has transformed Norman Mineta ...San Jose International Airport, infamously known for having a terminal that resembled a bus station, into one of the world's most tech-hip airports.

The upgrades are both obvious and unseen, ranging from an abundance of power and USB ports embedded in specially designed chairs for always-on travelers to cutting-edge baggage x-ray machines below deck.

The end result is a gateway that represents the pulse of Silicon Valley. The new Terminal B, which replaces the 1960s era Terminal C, will be completely open on June 30. Terminal A also receiveda make-over, giving the airport an entirely new feel.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message:
The big lavender building on the edge of downtown San Jose that opened its doors 20 years ago this month has become the go-to place for international groups hoping to emulate its model as a hands-on children's museum. While many museums rely mostly on admission fees, grants and subsidies to survive, the Children's Discovery Museum is actually bringing in hundreds of thousands of dollars a year by renting and selling its own exhibits.

"We've done the roller coaster, but we continue to survive," said Marilee Jennings, executive director of the Children's Discovery Museum. "I often think we're the little engine that could."

status_message: How's Friday going for you?

Click here to read the report on the World Cup opening ceremonies and to see a slide show of over a hundred photos from the event and around the world. http://www.mercurynews.com/top-stories/ci_15276192

DAVID CRARY,Associated Press

The first World Cup ever held in Africa opened Friday in a dazzling burst of joy, color and noise — and just a tinge of sadness.

Before a jubilant, horn-blowing crowd at Soccer City, the spectacular stadium between Johannesburg and Soweto, hundreds of African dancers in vivid greens, reds and yellows paraded onto the field for the opening ceremony of the month-long tournament.

Most of the fans were in the yellow jerseys of Bafana Bafana, the host country's team, which was playing Mexico following the pageantry.

The elation was tempered by news that Nelson Mandela, the revered anti-apartheid leader and former president, would not attend the ceremony. The 91-year-old Mandela is frail and decided not to come after his 13-year-old great-granddaughter was killed in a car crash on the way home from Thursday night's World Cup concert.

Several other icons of the anti-apartheid struggle in South Africa were on hand — including Mandela's former wife, Winnie, and Archbishop Desmond Tutu, who at one point was dancing in his seat to the music.
link_name: World Cup opening ceremony dazzles

An enlightening video slide show of how asparagus is grown and harvested. Full of "oh... I didn't know that" kind-of info.

Grown Locally, Feed Globally
Jackie Burrell writes:

The green stalks poke upward, fingerlike, from their mounds, their purple tips vivid in the early morning light. Bent over farmworkers move from row to row, their long-handled knives cutting each asparagus spear one by one.

If you bought your bundle of spears, bound with a purple rubber band, at a supermarket or Costco — or you live in Japan or Switzerland — chances are your asparagus began here, 10 inches below the surface of the earth. Furrowed farms across the Sacramento River Delta supply this quintessential spring vegetable, which can grow an astounding five inches overnight, to the world. 

http://www.mercurynews.com/food-wine/ci_14900523
link_name: Asparagus, the glorious vegetable of spring

Sue McAllister reports:

Silicon Valley median home price rises 29 percent

The median price of Santa Clara County houses sold last month rose 29 percent from a year earlier, to $550,000, the biggest year-over-year increase in almost a decade, a real estate information firm reported today.

The last time the median price rose more steeply from the year before was in October 2000, when the median price was $490,000.

Last month's median price was also up from $510,500 in February, according to a monthly report from MDA DataQuick, which gathered the data from public records. Click the link to read more.

J.M. Brown reports Santa Cruz City Council approves installation of meters to help panhandlers

When you see a red meter downtown in the next couple months, don't put coins in it if you think you're paying to park.

But do put money in it if you want to fund outreach services for panhandlers.

On Tuesday, the City Council unanimously approved bringing meters from the 1950s out of retirement for a new program called Imagine Positive Change. Up to eight meters featuring a metal corona saying "Imagine" will be placed on
 highly visible corners on Pacific Avenue to collect change for bus fare, state IDs and other ways to help panhandlers. Click the link to read more: http://www.mercurynews.com/search/ci_14878028

Chinese authorities raced against time, distance and wind in a remote corner of the Tibetan plateau as they tried to rescue victims from a 7.1 magnitude earthquake that killed at least 400 people and injured more than 8,000 others.

The earthquake struck Wednesday morning in one of the most inaccessible reaches of China, Qinghai province's Yushu county. The 100,000 people in the area are mostly Tibetan, many of them making their living herding yaks and sheep.

Houses of mud and wooden beams gave way almost immediately when the tremor struck at 7:49 a.m. in the county seat of Jiegu. A series of aftershocks collapsed schools built of concrete and a pagoda in the main park.

To view more images from the area and for more of the story click here: http://www.mercurynews.com/top-stories/ci_14881020
(Note: Some of the images may be too graphic for some)
link_name: 7.1 quake in western China kills 400, injures thousands

One thousand, three hundred, thirty-three.

For months, Warriors coach Don Nelson has downplayed this number as just one of many, the product of him being on the sidelines since before the first Rocky movie was released.

But Wednesday, Nelson reached this magic number, and it inked his name in the history books. With a 116-107 win over Minnesota, Nelson passed Lenny Wilkens as the winningest coach in NBA history.

And as his players mobbed him — jumping on him, messing up his hair, pouring Gatorade cups full of Mountain Dew all over him — it was clear this was more than just one of many numbers. status_message:
Ready for the rain to end?

Bruce Newman writes: After downpours, San Jose inches closer to surpassing 30-year rainfall average for April
http://www.mercurynews.com/top-stories/ci_14825782

It's the magic number that almost everybody in San Jose obsesses over, although nobody seems to actually know what it is. It determines whether lawns in Little Portugal turn brown by June, whether flowers bloom in Blossom Valley, whether bathers in Burbank finish their showers with soap in their eyes. It determines whether the weather is good or bad.

The number is 15.08, which is how many inches of rain San Jose is supposed to get in an average wet season. And after a downpour of .53 inches that soaked the city Sunday night and Monday morning, San Jose was looking like the children of Lake Wobegone: waterlogged and slightly above average. With a seasonal total of 14.34 inches of rain, according to the National Weather Service, the city was within another couple of good soakers — .74 inches, to be exact — of exceeding the 30-year average.

status_message:
Anyone get a traffic ticket lately? How much was it for?

Gary Richards reports: Why traffic tickets can cost hundreds of dollars
http://www.mercurynews.com/ci_14821297

When Sgt. Eddie Chan makes traffic stops, the San Jose officer makes it a point never to tell drivers how much their ticket will cost. He's afraid they'll go ballistic.

Fines on traffic tickets have surged in the past five years as the state has added fees and penalties that can raise the cost of most infractions into the hundreds of dollars. Running a red light: $446. Driving solo in the car-pool lane: $445. Speeding at 81 mph on most freeways: at least $331. Ignoring a "don't walk" sign: $173.

And for moving violations, tack on an extra $50 if you go to traffic school to keep your record clean.

Even fix-it tickets that once cost nothing to resolve, like a broken headlight, now run $25.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message:
Beeper Eggs emit a joyous noise to Bay Area blind kids
http://www.mercurynews.com/top-stories/ci_14816049

Bruce Newman reports
Crickets! That's what the oblong orbs — glittering purple and pink plastic eggs — sounded like as Audrey Nicholson, 3, held each one up to her ear.

This was Audrey's haul from the Beeper Egg Hunt, which the Blind Babies Foundation rolled out here Saturday at Midtown Terrace Park. The eggs, hundreds of them, emitted an electronic chirrup, and the kids spread out across the broad expanse of grass, following the sound with empty Easter baskets.

From a basket filled with these curiously chirping objects, Audrey plucked 20 or 30 eggs in quick succession, whipping them behind her back like missiles. Audrey has no eyes, so there was no chance that her routine was anything other than precociousness.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message:
San Jose Great Bunny Rescue was a success

Linda Goldston writes: Where have all the bunnies gone?

This time last year, there were hundreds of bunnies scampering through Moreland Woods next to San Jose's Easterbook Discovery School. Some were abandoned Easter bunnies, some were the product of what bunnies do — breed like crazy if they aren't spayed or neutered — and some were dead, killed by kids with BB guns or dogs illegally allowed to chase them inside the fenced-in lot.

On Friday afternoon, under gray skies and the threat of rain, there were none in sight — dead or alive. It was a sign of the success of the Great Bunny Rescue of 2009, when three rescue groups were able to trap more than 100 bunnies.
link_name: www.mercurynews.com

status_message:
Here's a great story from Matt Wilson I wanted to share with you guys.

Center's Alzheimer's patients paint what they can't say

It's been decades since Howard Saunders retired as a draftsman, but once a week for the past six years, the 88-year-old picks up a paintbrush and spends the afternoon creating images. It's a routine he rarely breaks-and one that has helped him better cope with the effects of Alzheimer's disease. On a recent Tuesday, Saunders carefully added the final spots and details to a cheetah painting.

Saunders is part of the Memories in the Making art program, aimed at using art to help those afflicted with Alzheimer's and dementia piece their memories back together. The Alzheimer's Association of Northern California has operated the program for more than a decade, and currently offer classes at 30 residential and adult day programs throughout the Bay Area, including Cupertino, Los Gatos and San Jose.
link_name: www.mercurynews.com

Ever been sitting on a plane on the tarmac for an extended period of time? Share your story with us.
-----------------
Stinky toilets, crying babies, airless cabins—the Obama administration said Monday passengers don't have to take it any more. It ordered airlines to let people get off planes delayed on the ground after three hours.

Transportation Secretary Ray LaHood said the three-hour limit and other new regulations are meant to send an unequivocal message to airlines not to hold passengers hostage on stuck planes. Coming on the eve of the busy holiday travel season, the announcement was hailed by consumer advocates as "a Christmas miracle."
link_name: Gov't imposes 3-hour limit on tarmac strandings - San Jose Mercury News

Pink Slip Guide to Surviving the Holidays

If you're unemployed now or have recently gone back to work, writer Pat May is looking for first-hand tips on dealing with Christmas craziness. Feel free to think as broadly and as creatively as you like. What have you done, say, to stretch your dollars for gifts and year-end activities during a time of tight household budgets?

He's open to any tips you might have that will hopefully help other readers who are in the same boat.

Feel free to list your ideas in an email, and know that he may edit them down for space. OR you can call him and run some of your suggestions by him on the phone.

Contact pmay@mercurynews.com or call 408-920-5689
